    "summary": "Objection to \"constitutive nature\" — too technical",
    "content": "I voted \"defining nature\" over \"constitutive nature.\" My specific objection:\n\n**\"Constitutive\" is a term of art that imports its own philosophical framework.** In Kantian usage, \"constitutive\" contrasts with \"regulative\" and carries specific technical meaning about what *makes experience possible*. In phenomenology, \"constitutive analysis\" means something precise about how consciousness structures objects. A reader trained in either tradition will read \"constitutive nature\" through those lenses — and the author is doing neither Kantian constitution nor Husserlian constitutive analysis. The author's 德 is assembled through inductive generalization and normative imposition, not through transcendental or phenomenological constitution.\n\n\"Defining\" is plain English. Everyone knows what \"defining\" means. It carries no hidden philosophical freight, and it maps directly to the author's own word: 定义 (definition). The author literally describes the process as properties becoming definitions.\n\nThat said — \"constitutive nature\" is not *wrong*. It is my second choice. If the team prefers it, I would not object. The gap between \"defining nature\" and \"constitutive nature\" is small compared to the gap between either of them and \"virtue.\""
  }
